If there is an array of numbers, the prefix sum at any index $i$ is the sum of all elements from the very beginning of the array up to that index $i$.
prefix means all the elements before the current index and sum means the accumulation of those elements.
The prefix sum pattern is a powerful technique that allows us to efficiently calculate the sum of elements in a subarray.
 By precomputing the prefix sums, we can quickly determine the sum of any subarray in constant time.

To use this pattern effectively, you typically allocate an extra array (the "buffer space") of the same size as your input to store those cumulative totals.

Method                Space Complexity            Best For...
Auxiliary Array       O(N)                        When you need to answer many range sum queries (L to R) repeatedly.
In-Place Array        O(1)                        When you only need the prefix sums and don't care about losing the original values.
Hash Map + Variable   O(N)                        "When searching for specific subarray sums or patterns (e.g., ""Longest subarray with sum K"")."



Prefix sum helps when:
You need subarray sum quickly
You see “continuous / contiguous”


